text:
Imagine having the building skills of gura...
I mean I know I spent around 6 months making unusually large life sized maps for hunger games maps on ps4 where there are no commands, and I ended up having to memorize huge strings of numbers for circles the size of the largest map setting, so I'm sure this is somewhat more normal for most of you more sane people, but still...

I mean I can literally see her thought process for every little move she makes when building and the moment she decides on the wrong dimensions or decides to place the blocks wrong and practically predict what she's going to be doing 5 steps in the future only to be proven wrong after 3 steps as she's only thought it halfway through...

I mean I honestly didn't think the whole thing about skill levels being so far apart that one can read their opponents minds was true, especially since it originated from anime, but holy hell, this is on the level where it's impossible not to read... is it actually possible to be this bad at something? either she's the best actor in the world or one of the worst builders, because I honestly can't convince myself that she's faking it.

as a child I used to think everything was related to time and effort rather than talent, because I had never run into a situation where someone was so good at something that I couldn't reach their level with around 2 months of effort, whether it be in competitive pvp games or complex pve games, but now I can say for sure, there is no such thing as talent, but there is such a thing as THIS. whatever THIS is. the opposite of talent. a weakness? a inability to succeed? a refusal to have any form of innovative or efficient thought simply when it comes to building? willful ignorance? a force of will so powerful that she feels no need to build better or faster as she feels that the current pace is sufficient? a lacking concept of time or driving force of urgency? does she seriously value the journey more than the objective? I can't tell if this is a weakness so powerful that it's a strength, or if this is a strength so powerful that it's a weakness, or both?!?!

this isn't just simply starting off and being new to something, she's played enough on stream alone to be half decent at building compared to how fast the usual player improves, so what exactly is blocking her progress? most people progressing this slowly are either children just learning the basics of counting and building, or adults just learning how a game works in the first place...

I'm just gonna assume being a vtuber has some other kind of added difficulty or maybe there is such a thing as being so naturally untalented, but whatever it's not like any of us are gonna stop being fans just because she places every block slightly off or every line slightly off. but it isn't just here that I've noticed it, but every other youtuber who builds in a video or a stream seems to have a kind of crippling disability only when it comes to building. is it like some kind of reflection of mental stat distribution? put all your intelligence into networking rather than logic? a social genius but logically challenged? is that just how popular people are? wait maybe it just depends on how much effort you put into improving it? maybe some people don't understand the answers to most math problems but just know it by memory and that's why they need to work it out on paper?

sorry at this point I'm just rambling more for the sake of my own understanding rather than for the sake of a comment, but damn if this aint mystifying as heck. I'm sure you can agree, even if you're one of those guys who never put much effort into building or math, I'm sure you can see what I'm talking about with her building, otherwise you'd probably be out somewhere making cash with your networking skills.

text:
For those wondering how Gura "broke" the elevator, it's a very technical error that I honestly don't expect Gura to have known about or even to have noticed. It's pretty unintuitive. But if you go to roughly 33:30 in the video, you'll see her accidentally place a torch on the hatch while trying to open it to exit. So what the magma does is produce a column of air bubbles to the highest source block above it, these bubbles provide air preventing you from drowning and accelerate you downwards. But when the the torch was place it temporarily broke the line of water blocks, and therefore broke the bubbles, and it doesn't reset naturally. (You can see the line of bubbles when she's going down, then when she looks back at the elevator after exiting you'll notice the bubbles are now gone.) You have to break the magma block and replace it, or plant seaweed or something to trigger a block update. Since we've got no video of it, we can't be sure why Kiara dies, but I'd assume it's just that she's used to not worrying about breathing when going down that elevator, and was either distracted or typing something when she started taking damage, and perhaps panicked when trying to exit the elevator; thereby drowning.
(Edit: As corrected by Arnav Mummineni in the replies: I stand corrected here, what's actually happening is that the torch destroys the water block it's placed in, which is actually creating an 'invisible' air gap there. Flowing water from the block above flows down hiding the gap, but bubbles can't propagate upwards through flowing water. So a fresh source block would need to be placed into the gap by either bucketing it in, or using seaweed to make a 'waterlogged block' and then allowing the bubbles to return to full height. The shaders probably don't help, but I confess even knowing now what happened, with basic textures, I can't tell the difference visually between the source blocks and the one flowing block between. So I still think it's very reasonable for Gura not to have noticed this.)

text:
"You have to break the magma block and replace it, or plant seaweed or something to trigger a block update."
No, just giving a block update wouldn't do anything since the source block would still be missing. To replace it, you would either have to use a water bucket to place a water source at the missing point, or grow kelp or seaweed into the missing source (since waterlogged blocks, which include kelp and seaweed, can only be water sources, not flowing water, when they replace a flowing water like the downwards flowing water that would be in the column, it replaces it with a source block, so once the kelp/seaweed is removed, the entire column is water), and once the entire column is water, the bubble column would return to it's full height.

author: @Windswrath

text:
¬†@danielblair4413¬† They really can't though. Not unless they mod the game or make an absolute monstrosity of a science project that takes immense technical knowledge (and also won't look good since you'll have tons of flying machine parts all over around it). 

They're struggling on basic things like following a blueprint of a circle and placing pixels in the right place, there's no way they're on the level to pull something like that off yet. Not that they're bad at the game though, they're just new, they need to learn things like basic game controls and mechanics before going into advanced stuff like that.

Technical Minecraft is one heck of a challenge, people can play the game for thousands of hours and still not have a good grasp of the technical parts of it. Give them another 5+ years of Minecraft and maybe something like that could start looking more like a realistic challenge.
